    # Policy documents
    {"title": "UK Innovation Strategy 2025-2030", "content": "The UK Innovation Strategy sets out the government's vision for making the UK a global hub for innovation. Key priorities include: 1) Unleashing business innovation through R&D tax credits and the Patent Box scheme, 2) Supporting people and skills through the Global Talent Visa and STEM education initiatives, 3) Building innovation institutions including catapult centres and regulatory sandboxes, 4) Driving innovation in every region through Levelling Up funds and regional innovation clusters, 5) International collaboration through Horizon Europe association and bilateral science agreements. The strategy commits £22 billion annually to R&D by 2026 and aims to make the UK the most innovative economy in the world.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "Innovator Founder Visa Requirements and Criteria", "content": "The UK Innovator Founder Visa (replacing the Innovator Visa from April 2023) is designed for experienced business people seeking to establish an innovative business in the UK. Key requirements: 1) Endorsement from an approved endorsing body, 2) The business idea must be innovative - genuinely new or significantly different from anything else on the market, 3) The idea must be viable - with evidence of a realistic business model and market, 4) The idea must be scalable - potential for significant growth, creating jobs and economic impact, 5) The applicant must have at least £50,000 in investment funds, 6) English language proficiency at B2 level. The endorsing body assesses the innovation, viability, and scalability criteria. Successful applicants receive a 3-year visa with a path to settlement.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "Innovate UK Smart Grants Programme Guide", "content": "Innovate UK Smart Grants provide up to £500,000 for innovative projects with strong commercial potential. The programme is open to UK-registered businesses of any size, working alone or in collaboration. Assessment criteria: 1) Innovation (how novel and ambitious the idea is), 2) Market opportunity (evidence of customer demand and market size), 3) Team (skills, experience, and track record), 4) Project plan (deliverability, milestones, and risk management), 5) Value for money (justification of costs and expected return on investment). Applications are assessed by independent experts and compete against other applications in the same round. Funding covers 50-70% of eligible project costs depending on company size.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "UKRI Technology Readiness Levels Framework", "content": "UKRI uses Technology Readiness Levels (TRLs) to assess the maturity of innovations. TRL 1: Basic research, TRL 2: Technology concept formulated, TRL 3: Proof of concept, TRL 4: Technology validated in lab, TRL 5: Technology validated in relevant environment, TRL 6: Technology demonstrated in relevant environment, TRL 7: System prototype in operational environment, TRL 8: Actual system completed and qualified, TRL 9: Actual system proven in operational environment. Most Innovate UK grants target TRL 3-7, bridging the 'valley of death' between research and commercialisation. Understanding your TRL helps you target the right funding programme.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "UK Intellectual Property Strategy for Innovators", "content": "The UK's intellectual property framework is a key asset for innovators. Key elements: 1) Patents - 20-year protection for novel inventions, UK IPO offers fast-track 'Green Channel' for environmentally beneficial inventions, 2) Trade marks - protection for brand identity, online registration available, 3) Design rights - automatic protection for original designs, registered designs offer stronger protection, 4) Trade secrets - protection through NDAs and employment contracts, 5) The Patent Box regime reduces corporation tax on profits from patented inventions to 10%. UK IP rights are enforceable globally through international treaties and are a key consideration for visa endorsement bodies assessing innovation.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "Net Zero Innovation Portfolio", "content": "The UK government's £1 billion Net Zero Innovation Portfolio funds the development of low-carbon technologies across 10 priority areas: 1) Advanced nuclear, 2) Hydrogen production and storage, 3) Carbon capture, utilisation and storage, 4) Green finance, 5) Sustainable aviation fuel, 6) Industrial decarbonisation, 7) Smart energy systems, 8) Natural environment, 9) Buildings, 10) Future transport. The portfolio supports projects from proof of concept through to large-scale demonstration, with additional funding from matched industry investment.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": None},
    {"title": "UK Digital Strategy: Digital Skills and Infrastructure", "content": "The UK Digital Strategy focuses on three pillars: 1) Digital infrastructure - £5 billion for gigabit broadband and nationwide 5G coverage by 2030, 2) Digital skills - the National Skills Fund provides £2.5 billion for digital training, coding bootcamps, and AI literacy programmes, 3) Digital government - all public services to be available digitally, with £1.2 billion invested in NHS digital transformation. The strategy also addresses digital inclusion, ensuring 95% of the population has basic digital skills by 2030.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "IT"},
    {"title": "Post-Brexit Trade and Innovation Policy", "content": "The UK's post-Brexit trade policy creates new opportunities for innovative businesses. Key elements: 1) Independent trade agreements with fast-growing markets (Australia, Japan, CPTPP), 2) The UK's own regulatory frameworks allow faster innovation in areas like AI, genomics, and autonomous vehicles, 3) The Global Innovation Fund supports UK-international research collaboration, 4) The Developing Countries Trading Scheme provides preferential access for UK innovations in emerging markets. While EU market access requires regulatory alignment, the UK's regulatory autonomy enables innovation in areas where EU rules are more restrictive.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "Business"},
    {"title": "NHS Long Term Plan: Technology and Innovation", "content": "The NHS Long Term Plan commits to: 1) Every patient having access to digital GP services by 2024, 2) AI screening for cancer, cardiovascular disease, and eye conditions rolled out across all NHS trusts, 3) A new NHS Innovation Service to help innovators navigate the health system, 4) £250 million annual funding for NHS clinical research with technology companies, 5) Digital-first approach to outpatient appointments, with 30% conducted remotely. The plan specifically encourages partnerships with technology startups and has created 15 NHS Innovation Accelerators to fast-track promising technologies.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "Health"},
    {"title": "DEFRA Environmental Land Management Scheme", "content": "The Environmental Land Management (ELM) scheme replaces EU Common Agricultural Policy payments in England. The scheme pays farmers for environmental outcomes including: 1) Sustainable Farming Incentive - standards for soil health, integrated pest management, and nutrient management, 2) Local Nature Recovery - habitat creation and restoration, 3) Landscape Recovery - large-scale ecosystem restoration. Technology plays a key role: satellite monitoring verifies compliance, IoT sensors measure environmental outcomes, and digital platforms facilitate payment administration. The scheme creates opportunities for AgriTech companies providing monitoring and verification tools.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "Agriculture"},
    {"title": "UK AI Regulation: Pro-Innovation Approach", "content": "The UK government has adopted a pro-innovation approach to AI regulation, avoiding a single AI regulator in favour of sector-specific oversight. Key principles: 1) Safety and security, 2) Transparency and explainability, 3) Fairness and non-discrimination, 4) Accountability and governance, 5) Contestability and redress. The approach gives UK AI companies more flexibility than the EU AI Act, potentially creating a competitive advantage. The AI Safety Institute, based in London, leads global AI safety research and testing.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "IT"},
    {"title": "UK Fintech Strategy and Regulatory Sandbox", "content": "The UK's fintech strategy positions London as the global fintech capital through: 1) The FCA Regulatory Sandbox allowing innovative firms to test products with real customers under relaxed regulations, 2) Open Banking and the move towards Open Finance giving consumers control over their financial data, 3) The Fintech Bridges programme establishing regulatory cooperation with 30+ countries, 4) The Bank of England's approach to stablecoins and Central Bank Digital Currency research, 5) R&D tax credits specifically enhanced for financial services innovation.", "doc_type": DocType.policy, "sector": "Business"},
    # Research papers
    {"title": "Transformer Models for Medical Image Analysis: A UK Multi-Centre Study", "content": "This peer-reviewed study from Imperial College London, University of Edinburgh, and King's College London evaluated vision transformer models for analysing 500,000 medical images across 12 NHS trusts. The models achieved radiologist-level accuracy (AUC 0.98) for detecting lung nodules, brain haemorrhages, and breast lesions. The study demonstrates that AI diagnostic tools can significantly reduce reporting backlogs in the NHS, where 28% of radiology positions are unfilled. The research was funded by UKRI and the Wellcome Trust.", "doc_type": DocType.research, "sector": "Health"},
    {"title": "Federated Learning Privacy Guarantees: Theoretical Framework and UK Applications", "content": "This Cambridge University paper establishes mathematical privacy guarantees for federated learning systems deployed in UK healthcare and finance contexts. The framework proves that with differential privacy noise calibrated to ε=1.0, individual data records cannot be reconstructed with probability exceeding 10^-6. Practical applications include multi-bank fraud detection and cross-trust NHS AI training, both of which face strict data protection requirements under UK GDPR.", "doc_type": DocType.research, "sector": "IT"},
    {"title": "Economic Impact of AgriTech Adoption on UK Small Farms", "content": "This DEFRA-commissioned study by the University of Reading quantifies the economic impact of technology adoption on UK farms under 200 hectares. Results from 1,500 farms show that precision agriculture technologies increase net profit by £45/hectare on average, IoT soil sensors reduce fertiliser costs by 22%, and GPS-guided machinery reduces overlap waste by 15%. However, adoption barriers include high upfront costs, lack of rural broadband, and limited technical skills.", "doc_type": DocType.research, "sector": "Agriculture"},
